explanation:
For MISRA rule checking of out-of-bounds use of <string.h> functions you must examine any callees and data they touch that could call string functions or pass pointers/sizes to them. Each listed symbol is required for that analysis:

- OS_SocketBindAddress: direct callee of OS_SocketBind; its body may call string functions or pass buffers derived from Addr/sock_id.
- OS_SocketListen: direct callee of OS_SocketBind; its body may call string functions or manipulate name/buffer fields that could overflow.
- OS_SocketBindAddress_Impl: implementation-level routine called by OS_SocketBindAddress; likely contains platform-specific operations where string.h functions (strncpy/memcpy/etc.) may be used.
- OS_SocketListen_Impl: implementation-level routine called by OS_SocketListen; must be checked for string operations on internal buffers.
- OS_CreateSocketName: function that constructs socket names; very likely to use strncpy/strncat/memset/strlen and must be inspected for correct buffer length usage and NUL-termination.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: retrieves object records (names/strings); may copy or return pointers to name buffers used with string functions.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: may parse/convert object tokens including string manipulations; needed to see how strings/tokens and lengths are handled.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: may perform cleanup or buffer operations on object names; include to see any string handling.
- OS_printf: formatting wrappers sometimes use snprintf internally or are used by callees to format strings; inspect to ensure no caller-supplied buffers are overrun.
- OS_SockAddr_t: the sockaddr type definition is required to know what fields (char arrays, lengths, pointers) are passed to string functions and their sizes.
- osal_id_t: type of sock_id; required to trace how IDs index object tables that contain name buffers or pointers used in string routines.
- OS_SUCCESS: return-code constant required to disambiguate control flow (whether subsequent callees are invoked) when reasoning about whether any string calls can be reached.
- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_TYPE: return-code constant used in the special-case branch in OS_SocketBind; needed to know whether the path that avoids listen() is taken.
- OS_MAX_API_NAME: common name-size macro used when allocating/copying object names; needed to check size arguments passed to strncpy/memcpy/etc. (include the actual macros used in the implementations).
- OS_MAX_PATH_LEN: common path/name buffer size macro (or equivalent size constant used by socket-name routines); needed to verify buffer bounds when creating or copying socket path strings.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType: present in the static graph (unit-test instrumentation); stubs may use memcpy/strlen to register/return values — include to ensure test-harness instrumentation does not introduce out-of-bounds string usage in the observed call path.
- UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData: unit-test/harness helper that can perform string/context copying; include for the same reason as other UT_ stubs.
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler: unit-test harness dispatcher that can call default handlers which may use string operations; include to rule out instrumentation-induced violations.
- UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: unit-test helper that may copy or return pointers to stub data (memcpy/strlen/etc.); include to ensure no hidden string operations affect the analyzed path.

In short: to determine MISRA <string.h> violations you must inspect the implementations that construct or copy socket/object names and any size macros or types that define buffer lengths; the listed functions/types/constants cover the direct callees of OS_SocketBind and the likely string-handling utilities they use (including unit-test stubs present in the static call graph).
